<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>1108</anchor>   <addr>axt-0042</addr>  <route>axt-0042.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>21</day></date>  <title>Kuratowski finiteness</title> <meta name="source"><link href="https://www.cs.bham.ac.uk/~mhe/TypeTopology/Fin.Kuratowski.html#1009" type="external">TypeTopology</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  A type <tex>X</tex> is called <b>finite</b> if there exists a natural number
  <tex>n</tex> and a surjective function <tex display="block">e :  \mathsf{Fin} ( n )   \twoheadrightarrow  X.</tex> Such a
  surjective map is called a <em>listing</em> of <tex>X</tex>.
</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related/> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>1109</anchor>  <taxon>Proposition</taxon> <addr>axt-0041</addr>  <route>axt-0041.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>21</day></date>   <meta name="source">Personal communication with <link href="martin-escardo.xml" type="local" title="Martín H. Escardó">Martín H. Escardó</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  Given a set <tex>X</tex>, the following are equivalent:
  <ul>    <li><tex>\mathcal{P} ( X )</tex> is a <link href="axt-0024.xml" type="local" title="Spectral locale">spectral frame</link>.</li>    <li><tex>X</tex> is <link href="axt-0042.xml" type="local" title="Kuratowski finiteness">Kuratowski-finite</link> and has decidable equality.</li>    <li><tex>X</tex> is Bishop-finite.</li>    <li><tex>\mathcal{P} ( X )</tex> is a Stone frame.</li>  </ul></p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>